The columns from the input data table that have meaningful data are displayed above, excluding the first column showing the ID of the galaxy. This is just used to match galaxies between the input and output catalogues. The data we have selected is of one primary type:

  1. Fluxes/Errors: These are the measured fluxes and their errors in 9 bands, after galatic extinction corrections. These are the primary measurements used in SED fitting to construct a model for each galaxy, so these should be included in our analysis as well.

There are a few columns that we ignore.

  1. Galaxy Positions
  2. Redshift
  3. Fluxes/Errors without corrections
  4. Galactic extinction corrections

We do not select galaxy positions (RA and DEC) since the Universe is homogeneous and isotropic, so the properties of galaxies should not vary between different survey areas. We do not select the redshift since this may be a parameter we want our model to predict. This would result in overfitting if we were to include spectroscopic redshifts in training our model to predict redshifts. We do not select the fluxes and errors without galactic extinction corrections, as well as the extinction corrections themselves, since this information should be encoded in the corrected fluxes/errors.

Question 3¶

It is often useful (and sometimes required) to normalize your data, i.e. for each parameter, subtract the mean of that parameter from each point in the sample, and divide by the standard deviation. For example, for mass, for each galaxy $i$, you can calculate

$$ M_{norm, i} = \frac{M_i - \langle M \rangle}{\sigma_M}$$

There are other ways to pre-process data (e.g., normalize by quantiles, or redefine variables such that they match some distribution).

  • For each column you chose, normalize the data in your sample in some way.
  • For one parameter, make a histogram of the original data, and the data after normalization. Do the histograms look as you expected them to?
In [5]:
# Define a function to calculated the normalized quantity
# for a parameter in the table
# Note: These are normalized by calculating the z-score as
#       defined above
def Normalize(table, col):

    # Extract the data for a given column
    X = table[col].values.T

    # Calculate the mean and standard deviation for the sample
    X_mean = np.mean(X)
    X_std = np.sqrt(np.var(X, ddof = 1))

    # Return the z-score
    return (X - X_mean) / X_std, X_mean, X_std

# End of function definition

In the figure above, the left plot shows the flux distribution in one band without normalizing the data. Here the data seems to resemble an exponential distribution with two peaks. This makes sense since if we look at the bivariate distribution of stellar mass and redshift, there are very few galaxies with low stellar mass and high redshift. These galaxies would have the lowest fluxes and would populate the area between the two peaks of the distribution.

The right plot illustrates the same as the left except we normalized each flux measurement according to the normalization defined in the question statement. Here we take each measurement, subtract off its mean and divide by the standard deviation (i.e., we calculate the z-score). The result of this should be to shift the distribution so that the mean value is at $0$ and its standard deviation is $1$. This shouldn't change the shape of the flux distribution, which is what we see comparing our two plots.

Section 1: Data Compression¶

Question 1¶

What is a dimensionality reduction technique? Why would you use one?

Dimensionality reduction techniques are algorithms that reduce the dimensions of a dataset while simultaneously losing as little information contained in the data as possible. For example, if our data consisted of $1000$ samples with $10$ data points each, the compression algorithm would attempt to reduce the number of data points per sample while representing the same information.

Dimensionality reduction techniques are mainly used to reduce computation time (i.e., the number of operations required) and/or the amount of information stored.

Question 2¶

There are many different data compression techniques: PCA, UMAP, tSNE, VAE... Pick two of these methods, and explain briefly:

  • How do each one of them work?
  • What are advantages or disadvantages of each method?
  • When would you use one over the other?

Two data compression techniques are PCA and UMAP:

  1. PCA: This method attempts to find the principle components of the data. That is, PCA attempts to transform the data into an orientation such that the variance of the projected data is maximized. Ignoring the principle components with less significance (i.e., components with a low fraction of total variance) leads to the dimensionality reduction. The main advantage of PCA is that it is a fast, simple algorithm where transforming the data by the principle components consists of linear operations. The main disadvantage is that if the original data does not lie on or near a lower-dimensional linear subspace, then many principle components will need to be retained in order to keep most of the information in the data.

  2. UMAP: This method attempts to embed high dimensional data by searching for a low dimensional projection of the data that has the closest possible equivalent to the original topological structure. It does this by using a cost function that weights preserving global and local structure in the data. The main advantage is UMAP is highly general meaning it can work well on large datasets with many dimensions where the data is non-linear. The main disadvantage is UMAP depends on several hyperparameters that need to be tuned for the dataset. The effectiveness of the embedding is significantly impacted by the choice of hyperparameters.

PCA is most useful if the data lies on or near a linear subspace. In this case, most of the data's information content is retained by the principle components representing the axes of the subspace. On the other hand, UMAP should be used if the data contains non-linear structure.

The figure above shows how the principle components vary with the stellar mass and redshift of each galaxy.

The left plot illustrates the variation with stellar mass. There is no discernible pattern within each cluster, however, it appears that the lower two clusters consist of galaxies with stellar masses above $10^{10} M_\odot$, while the upper cluster consists of galaxies with lower stellar masses below this mark.

The right plot depicts the variation with redshift. There is no discernible pattern between each cluster, however, it appears that their is some redshift variation between galaxies in the lower and upper clusters (i.e., the linear clusters). The plot shows that in these clusters, the redshift increases as we move towards $\rm{PC1} = 0$, although most of the variation is only seen at the lower end near $\rm{PC1} = 0$.

plt.show()

Compared to using PCA reduction, UMAP finds the data separates into 4 different clusters as opposed to 3. These clusters have more complex shapes compared to the PCA results. The large central cluster is crescent shaped and is mostly composed of low redshift objects with mid-to-high stellar masses. The smaller, quarter circle shaped cluster at the bottom right of the plot is conversely composed of high stellar mass objects at higher redshift.

There are also two sparse, linearly shaped clusters on either side of the largest cluster. These clusters have opposite features. The left one consists of low stellar mass, low redshift objects, while the right one consists of high stellar mass, high redshift objects.

For the UMAP algorithm, the hyperparameter "n_neighbors" controls the degree of local to large scale clustering. For our data, using a low value (i.e., $N = 2$) results in a singular cloud containing all points with very minimal large scale structure. On the other hand, using a high value (i.e., $N = 200$) doesn't change the clustering much for our sample compared to our fiducial case of $N = 15$. The only real difference is the orientation of the clusters in the $2$D reduced space.

Question 1¶

Choose a clustering algorithm. Why did you go for this particular one?

The clustering algorithm I chose is Spectral Clustering. For our data, it has a few advantages over other methods:

  1. The data isn't Gaussian distributed so using Gaussian Mixture Models wouldn't be suitable.
  2. The clusters we find visually in Section 1 (for the UMAP reduction) have complex shapes, some of which are non-circular, indicating that K-means is unlikely to split the clusters correctly since this method prefers to create circular clusters.

# Import Libraries
from sklearn.cluster import SpectralClustering
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score

# Extract the UMAP data
UMAP_DATA_new = np.zeros((len(UMAP_cat['id'].values), 2))
UMAP_DATA_new[:, 0] = UMAP_cat['PC1'].values
UMAP_DATA_new[:, 1] = UMAP_cat['PC2'].values

# Set the hyperparameters for our algorithm
n_jobs = 4
gamma = 0.1

# Set the number of cluster lists
n_list = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8]

# Loop through different numbers of clusters
scores = np.zeros(len(n_list))
for i in range(0, len(n_list)):

    # Apply clustering to our data
    cluster = SpectralClustering(n_clusters = n_list[i],
                                 n_jobs = n_jobs,
                                 gamma = gamma,
                                 random_state = 30)

    labels = cluster.fit_predict(UMAP_DATA_new)

    # Measure and print the silhouette score for clustering
    scores[i] = silhouette_score(UMAP_DATA_new, labels)
    print('Silhouette Score for N = {0} clusters:'.format(n_list[i]), scores[i])

# End of for loop

It is clear from the plots above that redshift has the most statistically significant differences between the clusters.

Section 3: Supervised ML¶

Finally, we can use supervised ML to train an algorithm that predicts our relevant physical parameters (mass, redshift, etc.) from the input data directly. This is a regression task, since we want to predict a continuous variable.

You should aim to predict mass and redshift of galaxies, but you can also try to predict more properties available in the output catalog.

Question 1¶

Choose a regression tool (e.g., a linear model, SVM, neural network, gaussian process, decision tree... see more examples here).

Why did you choose this particular one?

  • You can either train N different models for mass, redshift, etc.; or you can train a single model that predicts N parameters simultaneously.
  • Think: how many variables do you want to predict, what does your data look like, what relationship do you see by eye between your input and output data...

The regression tool I chose is Decision Trees. For our data, it has a few advantages over other methods:

  1. SVMs generally work best as classifiers and here we are looking at a regression problem.
  2. Linear, Lasso, and Ridge regression fit models that are linear in the model parameters, which may not be true in this case.
  3. Decision trees can capture non-linear relationships and they are more robust, working for most types of input data.

X_DATA = X_DATA[filter, :]

Y_DATA = Y_DATA[filter, :]
X_DATA = X_DATA[filter, :]

## Stellar Mass ##

# Search for the optimal parameters
search_Mass = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator = DT, param_distributions = params, n_iter = 1000, n_jobs = 4)

# Put the results into a dataframe
res_Mass = pd.DataFrame(search_Mass.cv_results_)

# Extract the models with the highest rank (by rank_test_score)
res_Mbest = res_Mass.query('rank_test_score == 1')

# Get the model hyperparameters for stellar mass
# Note: min_samples_leaf should be the same for all rank = 1 models
#       We want to choose the minimum max depth since higher values do
#       not improve the tree
min_samples_leaf_Mass = min(res_Mbest['param_min_samples_leaf'].values.T)
max_depth_Mass = min(res_Mbest['param_max_depth'].values.T)

# Train the best-fit model for stellar mass
DT_Mass = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth = max_depth_Mass,
                                min_samples_leaf = min_samples_leaf_Mass,
                                random_state = state)

The figure above shows the distributions for the training, validation, and test_sample.csv sets for one flux band and its error, after normalization. For test_sample.csv, the distribution was normalized using the same mean and standard deviation as the training and validation samples. Here we see that the training and validation samples have much greater overlap in their distributions compared to test_sample.csv. This is not only true for this particular band but all $9$ bands as well, compounding this effect.

This likely explains why the model performance is poor for test_sample.csv compared to the validation set. Decision trees are not good at extrapolation. The input data for the validation set looks much more similar to the training data compared to test_sample.csv.

## Stellar Mass ##

# Search for the optimal parameters
search_Mass = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator = DT, param_distributions = params, n_iter = 1000, n_jobs = 4)

# Put the results into a dataframe
res_Mass = pd.DataFrame(search_Mass.cv_results_)

# Extract the models with the highest rank (by rank_test_score)
res_Mbest = res_Mass.query('rank_test_score == 1')

# Get the model hyperparameters for stellar mass
# Note: min_samples_leaf should be the same for all rank = 1 models
#       We want to choose the minimum max depth since higher values do
#       not improve the tree
min_samples_leaf_Mass = min(res_Mbest['param_min_samples_leaf'].values.T)
max_depth_Mass = min(res_Mbest['param_max_depth'].values.T)

# Train the best-fit model for stellar mass
DT_Mass2 = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth = max_depth_Mass,
                                 min_samples_leaf = min_samples_leaf_Mass,
                                 random_state = state)

This is a bit surprising given that the UMAP compression of test_sample.csv overlaps well with the training set (as shown in the first plot below) and the model predictions for the validation set are fairly accurate.

This implies that there must be differences in the output physical properties we are trying to model between samples. If we look at the stellar mass and redshift distributions from Chang+2015, the training set the model is fit against and the validation set have distributions that overlap well. In contrast, these distributions for test_sample.csv look very different from the training set.

In particular, the stellar mass distribution for test_sample.csv has an excess number of low stellar mass galaxies ($M < 10^{10} M_\odot$) and the redshift distribution does not have enough intermediate-to-high redshift targets ($z > 0.2$). This is shown in the bottom two plots below where we plot the stellar mass and redshift distributions for test_sample.csv compared to the distributions of these parameters for the closest objects in the training set. To do this, we take each object in test_sample.csv, get its UMAP compression, and find its closest counterpart in the training set by Euclidean distance.

In [45]:
# Find the objects in test_sample.csv that are closest
# to the training set by UMAP compression
near_SM = np.zeros(X_SAMPLE_new.shape[0])
near_R = np.zeros(X_SAMPLE_new.shape[0])
for i in range(0, X_SAMPLE_new.shape[0]):

    # Calculate the distance between each point
    D = np.sqrt( (X_train[:, 0] - X_SAMPLE_new[i, 0])**2 + (X_train[:, 1] - X_SAMPLE_new[i, 1])**2 )

    # Find the position of minimum distance
    min_idx = np.where(D == min(D))[0][0]

    # Record the stellar mass and redshift of the
    # nearest UMAP coordinates
    near_SM[i] = Y_train[min_idx, 0]
    near_R[i] = Y_train[min_idx, 1]

# End of for loop
